## Decision

> Execute the full four-step Sales MIS cycle in a single sandbox run, writing and running my own openpyxl code per the manual, and produce `outputs/bank_daily_sales_dashboard_2025_completed.xlsx` with a per-sheet validation log. The environment is confirmed ready — python3 3.9.6 and openpyxl are both available — and the raw workbook is present with a known shape: `Daily Sales Data` carries 907 transaction rows (rows 2–908) across 17 columns, with the two achievement-percent columns (12 = Account Achievement %, 15 = Amount Achievement %) stored as Excel formulas (`=J2/K2`, `=M2/N2`) that a headless `data_only` read cannot evaluate.
>
> Concretely:
>
> This resolves the intent to a single concrete, best-fit process (the Complete Sales MIS Process) executed end-to-end, grounded in the confirmed environment and the manual's rules rather than a fixed script.
> **Step 1 — Load (§ Section 1):** Open `uploads/bank_daily_sales_2025.xlsx`, confirm the three sheets and the 17-column header on `Daily Sales Data`, and run the immediate sanity check so any schema drift or corrupt extract is caught before anything downstream trusts the file.
> **Step 2 — Sanity Check (§ Section 2):** Re-read with dynamic ranges — locate the header row and last data row by inspection (currently row 908) rather than hard-coding, since the source grows one row per transaction. Verify schema (all 17 expected columns present), count and calendar coverage (FY2025, the last row confirms 2025-12-31), duplicates (same date/branch/product/channel/RM), and nulls — but exclude columns 12 and 15 from the null check, instead **recomputing** their achievement percentages from the raw counts (J/K and M/N), because those cells hold uncached formulas. Name every anomaly in the report; drop nothing silently. Stage the clean, schema-validated result to a staged dataset file that every downstream step reads — never the raw file.
> **Step 3 — Slice & Dice (§ Section 3):** Read the staged dataset and fill `bank_daily_sales_dashboard_2025.xlsx`: KPI strip, monthly trend, asset/liability and channel-mix boxes, product performance, branch performance, RM leaderboard, top-10 branches, and the five bound charts. Derive product, branch and RM counts from the data itself and resize those data-driven sections (insert/delete rows, rewrite chart ranges and total rows). Leave structural sections at their fixed shape — twelve calendar months, the Asset/Liability split, the three channels, the top-10 cap — filling what's present and zeroing the rest rather than reshaping. Write reconciliation-checked totals as plain computed numbers, not Excel formulas. Save to `outputs/bank_daily_sales_dashboard_2025_completed.xlsx`.
> **Step 4 — Dashboard Validation (§ Section 4):** Independently recompute every headline total from the staged dataset and compare, sheet by sheet, against what landed in the completed dashboard — KPIs, monthly trend, product, branch and RM leaderboard sums — requiring each to tie back within the 0.5% reconciliation gap. Log a discrete **pass** or **fail** per check, never an averaged verdict. Per the ontology, the final status is exactly one of **validated** or **blocked**, with no hedge: the completed dashboard is released to Business and Leadership only if every sheet's check passes; if any single check fails, status is **blocked** and the failing sheet is named.

## Explanation

> I chose to run the entire four-step Sales MIS cycle (load, sanity check, slice-and-dice, and validation) in one sandbox pass because the environment is confirmed ready — python3 3.9.6 and openpyxl are both installed — and the raw workbook is present with a known structure of 907 transaction rows across 17 columns on the `Daily Sales Data` sheet. Rather than a fixed script, I'll write openpyxl code that follows the manual's rules directly, recomputing the two achievement-percent columns from their raw counts (since they're stored as uncached formulas a headless read can't evaluate), staging a validated dataset for all downstream steps, and releasing `outputs/bank_daily_sales_dashboard_2025_completed.xlsx` only if every per-sheet check ties back within the 0.5% reconciliation gap — otherwise marking it blocked and naming the failing sheet.

